AGI - The opposition protests against the new norms on the par condicio that give more space to the government and ministers in the electoral campaign.&nbsp; Sandro Ruotolo, Head of Information of the Democratic Party, after last night's vote on Rai&nbsp's Vigilance, observes that what happened has no precedent. "For the first time since the regulation was launched in 1993 - says - the par condicio no longer guarantees the proper conduct of the election campaign in public television because it allows ministers and undersecretaries to join the majority representatives in the last days of the election campaign, in this case for the European elections of 8 and 9 June, with the excuse of their institutional activities. A serious and dangerous act of force. Rules are not changed while the campaign is underway." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Critics also come from the M5s. The group leader in Vigilance Rai, Dario Caroallo, states that "the night in the Supervisory Board was written a bad page for Parliament and for public service. The majority of us have put an unacceptable attitude by rejecting any attempt to mediate on some of the problems we have raised, which is entirely unacceptable to the nature of a measure such as the parochial, which should serve to guarantee pluralism and to protect citizens." &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
To the attack also the group leader of the Green Left Alliance (AVS) in the Senate, Peppe De Cristofaro. "When they were in the opposition, the rules on the par-condicium were fine," he says. "Now that they are in the government, they change them to occupy even more spaces in public service with the excuse of institutional communication. Yesterday evening in the Supervisory Committee the right did not want to hear reasons and, strong of the support of Palazzo Chigi, voted by majority the regulation on the par condicio for the European elections of June. Then the 'Save Petrecca' rule, which will allow the most melonian of the Rai&nbsp directors, to air on RaiNews24 the comizi della Meloni without having to respond to violation of pluralism. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Forza Italia replies that "the narrative of non-existent occupations is not true". "Well the approval of the deliberation from the Supervisory Commission on the par condicio", reiterate in a note the president of the senators of Forza Italia, Maurizio Gasparri, the group leader in commission of Vigilance, Roberto Rosso, and the parliamentarians 'azzurri' Rita Dalla Chiesa and Andrea Orsini. "As a group of Forza Italia we hoped and shared the call in various amendments to the laws of 1993 and 2000, which regulate communication during the electoral campaigns, we would have wanted a wider convergence by the whole Commission. Minorities in some votes have paradoxically expressed themselves against the call for current norms and always evoked by them. Instead of sharing a balanced and meritorious decision, with principles often taken literally by delegates approved when the government had Count and the majority was far from political orientation." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"We have always acted for a shared, objective and respectful decision of laws in force and delibere Agcom - Fi's note continues - the principle of the different evaluation of the hourly bands has been accepted, for example, taking into account the number of spectators who change according to the hour. One prefers a non-truth narrative on non-existent occupations - the FI exponents emphasize - respect for truth, pluralism and the innovative indications of authority for communications. The embarrassment of the leftists appeared evident - concludes the note - they decided to tell a version of part by letting out from reality and so they did". &nbsp;

